PLAN
- Since 64 = 2^6, any multiplicative partition uses factors 2^k with k ≥ 1 and the sum of the k’s is 6.
- The unordered partitions of 6 (sum of k’s) correspond bijectively to multiplicative partitions of 64 via k_i ↦ 2^{k_i}.
- Therefore P(64) = p(6), the partition number of 6, which equals 11. (Explicitly, list the 11 partitions of 6 and their corresponding 2^{k_i} products.)

SOLUTION
- Let k_1, ..., k_m ≥ 1 with ∑ k_i = 6. The multiset {k_i} determines the multiplicative partition {2^{k_1}, ..., 2^{k_m}} of 64, and distinct multisets {k_i} give distinct partitions of 64.
- Hence P(64) = p(6) = 11.
- An explicit correspondence (by taking 2^{k_i}) yields the 11 partitions:
  64;
  2 × 32;
  4 × 16;
  16 × 2 × 2;
  8 × 8;
  8 × 4 × 2;
  8 × 2 × 2 × 2;
  4 × 4 × 4;
  4 × 4 × 2 × 2;
  4 × 2 × 2 × 2 × 2;
  2 × 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 × 2.

CHECK
- Consistency check: for P(40) with 40 = 2^3 · 5, the counting is more intricate due to mixing primes; but for pure powers of 2 (64), the method reduces to partitions of the exponent 6, giving p(6)=11. The listed 11 partitions are all distinct and multiply to 64, confirming the result.

FINAL
\boxed{11}
